'''Ibrahim''' or '''Brahim Jalti''' was a sergeant at the [[Royal Moroccan Army]] who, along with another soldier Jamal Zaim, denounced corruption in the army. They reported that high-ranking officials were employing soldiers in their own private farms. Ibrahim Jalti wanted to show the evidence directly to [[Mohammed VI]] and in 2002 took hostages demanding to meet the king. He was arrested and sentenced to 9 years in prison and the corruption evidence documents he had prepared were destroyed.<ref name=tq>{{cite news|last=Mehdi Sekkouri Alaoui|title=Interview. Brahim Jalti : "L’armée est plus dure que la prison"|url=http://www.telquel-online.com/archives/333/maroc3_333.shtml|accessdate=5 February 2014|newspaper=[[Telquel]]|date=N°333}}</ref>
In January 2014 Jalti, who is from Oujda,<ref>{{cite news|last=Omar Rifi|title=Le drame et la vérité|url=http://www.maghress.com/fr/lagazette/3074|accessdate=5 February 2014|newspaper=[[La Gazette du Maroc]]|date=7 July 2003}}</ref> started a sit-in near the Algerian border and published a document in which he denounces the corruption of officials from the army involved in cross-border smuggling.
